Vålådalen is located in Jämtland, I spent three nights here in august 2021. I photographed on top of Ottfjället,at the bottom of Ottsjön at the beach ridvadet and at the classic bend along vålån.

Söderåsens nationalpark is a deep valley surronded of lush beech woodland. I usually come here during late Spring and peak-color autumn. Most people photograph the impressive valley but I'm more drawn to the edges of the woodland, where the forest suddenly drops, making for simplistic woodlands scenes.

The nature is varied, featuring lush deciduous forests, impressive talus slopes with high cliffs, flowing streams and panoramic views.
The long, deep fissure valley by Skäralid is especially frequented. It is a rift valley of immense scope with perpendicular cliffs that envelope the Skärån river running along the bottom. Other impressive sites are Odensjön lake in the Nackarpsdalen valley as well as the vantage points of Kopparhatten, Hjortsprånget and Lierna along the Skäralidsdalen valley.

Storulvån is located in Jämtland, close to the Norweigan border.
Storulvån fjällstation sits slightly above the tree line, overlooking the fjäll birch forests. It is surronded by multiple mountain peaks.

The Omberg Ecopark is located on the
eastern shore of Lake Vättern. Here you will
be captivated by splendid orchids and
enthralling myths. You can wander among old
giant oak trees and shady beechwood
forests, as well as enjoy the fantastic view
from Hjässan – Omberg’s highest point.

This photograph was taken near Söderåsen during autumn 2021. Most of the leaves are starting to disappear, which opens up the mountainside.

This image is really more about textures, there isn't much of a composition, but the branches and the orange and yellow leaves creates a beautiful, almost abstract image.

Mountain birch grow just at the edge of the treeline. They're very unique to the swedish mountains. I have always had a liking for these tiny trees since I saw them. 
This photograph was taken at Storulvån, Jämtland during sunset. As the cold evening arrives the mist rolls in, increasing the seperation between the background elements and the fjällbjörk.
This fjällbjörk stood out from the rest and made for a great composition.

This is a classic composition over the bend in Vålån. Ever since I knew this place existed I had wanted to take this photograph. This is located in Vålådalen, Jämtland.
What I like about this photograph is that the bend in the river draws the viewer through the landscape, ending in the woodlands that never seem to end.

This photograph is taken from Ottfjället, looking down into the valley of Vålådalen. What really makes this composition work is the color. The pink wildflowers in the foreground draws the eye, then the rocks around the stream reflect the pink light from the sky. You follow that stream down the mountain, into the spruce forest with soft light, and finally out into the vast mountain landscape, with a pink and purple glow.
The colors flow all the way through the composition
The water level was lower than usual, this revealed a path in the rocks, making for a very good compensation. It was taken in the afternoon light, which can be seen hitting the trees in the far.

Right at the edge of the valley, I took this photo on a cold and misty may morning in 2021.
As the beech forest is in full bloom, this old tree had barely blossomed yet.
Its leaves have an entirely different colour of green compared to the rest of the forest. Its branches are also covered in moss. It's really those colour differences that makes the image work.

The composition is very unusual for a woodland, due to Söderåsens high canyon walls you can get a different angle on the woodland. The break of leaves in the image makes the tree pop out from the rest of the forest, and in the far background you see the steep cliffs surrounded by more beech forests.

After Forsakar waterfalls, runs a stream through the forests covered ravine.

What immediately takes your attention is the old tree stump. The contrast of the old brown wood, with the grey sand and white rocks. There is a lot of different earthy colours in the landscape. As long as the tree branches hanging down into the scene.

What really makes the image work is how the stream flows through the scene, starting in the left bottom corner, then going left and upwards. It makes you go through the entire photograph.

I took this photograph during my spring trip to southern Sweden. When I got home from the trip, I didn't consider this photograph especially good. But when I later revisited the photos I saw it's potential.
Seeing the waterfall through the almost lime green leaves is very pleasing, and one very unusual perspective of a waterfall. As it often seems from below and not above, and especially not with leaves in the way. The leaves really created an opening for the waterfall and frames it nicely. I also really like the pool of water below the waterfall.
I found this lookout when hiking in the winter. The sun was about to set and I got the last of light.

The snow was coming down heavy, so went out in my local area with my camera to see if I could find anything interesting. On my usual walk, I came across this tree along göta kanal.

The snowstorm had put a good amount of snow on the branches, and the contrast between the dark bark and the white snow really makes for a wonderful photograph. Meanwhile, the small branches are almost completely covered in snow. In the background you can see the thousands of snowflakes coming down.

The scene is intimidating with the branches almost coming out of the photograph and wrapping around you. Just the right amount of the tree is in the frame.

During autumn, in the mornings, ågelsjön often turn the surrondings into a misty paradise. On this occasion the birches across the lake are in full yellow and the lake is very calm.
Moments like these are fantastic, but they do not last very long. Barely an hour had passed until all the mist had blowed away and the mirrorlike reflections were no longer to be seen. 
Whilst the moment was beautiful, the compositions is a bit too minimalistic and lacks something. The mist was almost a little too thick, but it still makes for a great woodland photograph.

This photograph was taken in September 2020 in Söderåsen national park.
I walked past this scene and made a note of it in my mind, how close the tree was to the edge caught my interest. However later in the day, it started to rain heavily. I had to cover my camera with my lens cloth to protect it from all the rain. But the rain gave the landscape a very moody atmosphere. The wet leaves reflected the light from the overcast sky and made the landscape pop. The rain was so heavy that it became like fog, making the background less distracting.

What makes Söderåsen so special, and this composition works because the forests just drop in elevation.

One very foggy day I was hiking in Omberg. 
I thought going to my favourite lookout in the fog could be impressive, I had been there a few times before. 
While I was hiking up the mountain, I took another route to the lookout and came across this old oak. It barely had any branches left, and it had this weird thing up top.
What really made it special, is how the forests opened up around it. There wasn't any trees close to it.
The uniformity of the pines in the background makes the crocked oak really standout, and of course the mist made it absolutley perfect.

This is photograph is taken from my favourite lookout at Omberg during a summer evening.
It is a very remote part of Omberg that doesn't see many visitors, perhaps for the better, because it is incredibly steep, but that is what makes for the amazing views. 
This picture is taken towards the south, you can see the big hill covered in spruce and lush trees in golden light.
The composition is lacking but simple, but the texture of the shifting forests really makes the photograph enjoyable. Together with lake vättern in the background and the soft colorful sky.
The photograph captures the feeling of calm and endless summer.

Along the northern coast of Öland you can find these windswept pines. These forests are called trollskog.
This photograph is taken during sunrise, as you can see the golden light hitting the red pine, which amplify its color.
This picture is taken just at the edge of the forest, and you can see the pines closest to the camera have been affected more by the wind than the pines further back in the photograph.

Denna utställning består av 21 utvalda fotografier, uppdelade i sektionerna Göta Kanal, Östergötland och Norden. Fotografierna är som tidigast från 2017 och sträcker sig ända till 2023.
![bild](https://i.imgur.com/RiH5byC.jpeg)
Som en lokal fotograf från Ljungsbro har jag ägnat mitt arbete åt att fånga skönheten i vår omgivning. Min fotografiska resa började längs Göta Kanal och utvidgades senare till hela Östergötland, där de flesta av mina fotografier är tagna.
På senare tid har jag börjat utforska mer av Norden. Som ni kan se, inkluderar fotografierna de södra bokskogarna, den vida östkusten, de storslagna Jämtlandsfjällen, de norska fjordarna och de dramatiska norska bergen.

Fotografier går att beställa av fotografen. Till försäljning finns utskrifter, inramade utskrifter samt ett par canvas tavlor.

At the beginning of November, after my ["failed attempt"](/newsletter/early-autumn-2023) at capturing the autumn colors of the lush woodlands in the south, I decided to try once again.
!TIMELINE{soderasen,2023-11-04}
I arrived just before midnight in the dark, so I had not yet seen the autumn colors of the woodlands until I woke up. I could see that this time the colors had arrived in full force, it was indeed very beautiful.
  The first day I spent along the forests in the ridgelines, while I took many photos I was happy with, I revisited the same compositions the following day, in better conditions.   
I decided to go down the canyon and follow the flooded trail along the river.
!PHOTO(MK231104-2.jpg)
In the valley, there were more variations in the color, some oranges, but mostly yellow and green.
!PHOTO(MK231104.jpg)
A longer exposure created beautiful strokes of orange leaves and white bubbles in the river.  The following day, the valley and horizon were filled with mist, and there was some rain coming and going. On my last trip, I found a new lookout of the valley which I really enjoyed. I decided to go there again and to get a good look at the mists.
!PHOTO(MK231105-10.jpg)
The valley consisted of mostly dark red and deep orange colors, with some trees having lost most of their leaves. I really enjoy how well you can see the river and the curves of the valley. To the left upper corner, you can see some mist going into the woodland, so I decided to go towards that.
!PHOTO(MK231105-6.jpg)
The mist poking into the woodlands from the valley makes the landscapes a lot better. I really enjoy the variation of color in this scene, especially the contrast with the green leaves. What caught my attention first was the look down into the small stream, with the fallen tree and deep yellow colors. However, getting a tight composition of that proved difficult, so I ended up with a wider scene, which still worked out great. I like the contrast of the very sparse woodland to the left, while to the right the woodland is a lot tighter.  
I had some breakfast and waited for the mist to roll deeper into the woodland, thankfully I did not have to wait long.
!PHOTO(MK231105-5.jpg)
The small stream adds some great interest and detail to this scene, but the mist is really what makes me like this photo. I enjoy how the trees frame the scene, and how the branches leave a gap just where the mist is the thickest, so we get a beautiful view of the distant woodland.  
I went towards a tree I have photographed many times, in many different seasons. I had taken a picture of it in autumn 2021 but failed the composition slightly. This time there were more leaves in the valley, and I was determined to get a good composition of the tree.
!PHOTO(MK231105.jpg)
Photographing along the ridgeline makes for great compositions, and this tree is just so well placed at the edge. The colors were amazing in this scene, especially to that tree sticking up alone, higher than the rest. It had a beautiful fade of colors from dark red to yellow. One challenging part of the composition is the right upper corner, as the sky comes in, this time I tried covering it up more with leaves from a nearby branch, and I think it helped the scene a lot.  
However, while trying to pull the branch slightly more into the frame to cover more parts of the sky, my tripod fell over, and since my hands were occupied with the branch, I was unable to catch it in time. Luckily my Sony A7ii survived, but not my Sony 16-35 F4. It has been with me since 2019 when I bought it used for 9000 SEK, but luckily my insurance paid out the full amount I bought it for, so I have been using it for free for 4 years, not too bad!
!END
My autumn trip to Söderåsen was really amazing, the colors could not have been better!

I drove 4 hours south, arriving at Söderåsens national park late at night, starting off with sleep to start photographing the following morning. I knew before I came down that I was too early for the autumn colors I was hoping for, but I had the time and it is very hard to predict when the autumn colors will arrive, and for how long until the leaves fall off.
!TIMELINE{soderasen,2023-10-24}
As I arrived at night, I could not see the autumn colors in the dark. But when I woke up it was clear that the beach forests remained very green, with a few leaves turning yellow. However, once I reached the valley there were clearly more autumnal colors at the top of the trees. The following photo shows the still very green forests with yellow tops.
!PHOTO(MK231024-3.jpg)
Once I got to a lookout of the valley, I could see the mist rising from the bottom. There were a lot of colors in the valley, mostly yellow and green with a few oranges.
!PHOTO(MK231024-4.jpg)
As I mentioned earlier, the inner parts of the beech forests remained green, but there were a few yellow spots here and there. As the mist rolled into the woodland, it created a soft and beautiful atmosphere. The mist creates a much-needed separation from the distant trees.
!PHOTO(MK231024-6.jpg)
The few yellow spots convey the feeling of autumn, even though the forests are so green.
!PHOTO(MK231024-2.jpg)
The next morning there were once again patches of mist appearing in the valley. I found a lookout of the valley, which must be one of the lookouts with the furthest view of the valley, as it zigzags. I particularly like the small opening in the forest canopy, permitting a view of the river hiding below.
!PHOTO(MK231025-3.jpg)
The mist sometimes rolled into the woodland, I then had to be very quick, as it did not last long and came in small patches, making the photography high-paced and difficult. The following photo was rushed composition-wise, but it worked out.
!PHOTO(MK231025.jpg)
!END
I spent about 1-2 days photographing the woodlands and valleys of Söderåsen, I was blessed with beautiful mist, but the autumn colors I was hoping for were not there yet. I am hoping to be back in a week or two, to get a second attempt at the autumnal colors.
During the end of september, I spent 3 nights in Norway, with the goal of capturing beautiful autumn colors.

On the way towards Rondane, the autumn colors begun. The first photo was taken just along the roadside, in the foot of Rondane.
!PHOTO(MK230922.jpg)
Later along the way I turned onto a toll road, driving up to Dørålen. This road took me up to about 1000 meters above sea level, surrounded by mountains and beautiful birch trees.
The birch trees was just past their peak yellow color, some slightly orange and some almost without any leaves left.
Ironically, the best photo from that evening was of a barren birch tree, with just a few leaves at the top of the branches.
!PHOTO(MK230922-4.jpg)
With the beautiful view of the mountains, I had planned to shot a small lake for sunrise. I was not the only one with that idea, as there were multiple photographers at that lake that morning. It was cold and very calm, creating a beautiful reflection of the mountain. As the sun rose, it set the mountain birches on fire, in terms of color.
!PHOTO(MK230923.jpg)
I went back to where I spent the evening before shooting and wandered around the birch forest in the sunny weather. After a while, I found a small birch, with a very nice shape. I spent some time getting my composition right, balancing the tree and the mountains in the background.
!PHOTO(MK230923-3-2.jpg)
September and October are the best months for seeing the Milky Way. The national park has very low light pollution, making it possible to clearly see it with the naked eye. I had not tried photographing the Milky Way before, it was a fun challenge and I am very happy with the results.
!PHOTO(MK230923-2-2.jpg)

Fantastic colors.
 I really enjoyed it.
 !PHOTO(MK230924-6-2.jpg)

At the end of September, I spent 3 nights in Norway with the goal of capturing the beautiful autumn colors.
!TIMELINE{rondane,2023-09-22}
On the way to Rondane, the autumn colors began. The first photo was taken along the roadside, at the foot of Rondane.
!PHOTO(MK230922.jpg)
Further along the way, I turned onto a toll road, driving up to Dørålen. This road took me to about 1000 meters above sea level, surrounded by mountains and beautiful birch trees. The birch trees were just past their peak yellow color, some slightly orange, and some almost without any leaves left. Ironically, the best photo from that evening was of a barren birch tree, with just a few leaves at the top of the branches.
!PHOTO(MK230922-4.jpg)
With the beautiful view of the mountains, I had planned to shoot a small lake at sunrise. I was not the only one with that idea, as there were multiple photographers at that lake that morning. It was cold and very calm, creating a beautiful reflection of the mountain. As the sun rose, it set the mountain birches on fire in terms of color.
!PHOTO(MK230923-3.jpg)
I returned to where I had spent the evening before shooting and wandered around the birch forest in the sunny weather. After a while, I found a small birch with a very nice shape. I spent some time getting my composition right, balancing the tree and the mountains in the background.
!PHOTO(MK230923-12.jpg)
After spending the morning in the birch forest, I decided to explore the nearby area. Since the light was harsh, scouting for new photo locations was optimal. I decided to go to [Dørålseter](https://maps.app.goo.gl/td7juYD3A3EKJQco6), however, the road was closed for the last 5km. Luckily, I had brought my bike along on Yeti, so I could access it more easily. The following photo was captured along the road, looking in the direction of Dørålseter. I think the small plateaus look fantastic, a very unusual shape to witness in nature, especially how sharp the ridgelines are.
!PHOTO(MK230923-6.jpg)
Arriving at Dørålseter, the landscapes opened up more. The distant mountains had become larger, while the plateaus continued throughout the valley. The clouds had rolled in over the mountains, yet some light was able to make it through, creating this high-contrast scene of the birches in backlight, yet the sky filled with clouds.
!PHOTO(MK230923-14.jpg)
I finally got back to Yeti at around 15, needing a rest after photographing nonstop since 6 a.m. The sky was still filled with heavy clouds, but suddenly the sky opened up just enough for some light to hit a valley. The valley had caught my attention earlier, and this was a great opportunity.
!PHOTO(MK230923-10.jpg)
There was no particularly good light for sunset; however, once the darkness came, the sky cleared, and the Milky Way appeared. September and October are the best months for seeing the Milky Way. The national park has very low light pollution, making it possible to see it clearly with the naked eye. I had not tried photographing the Milky Way before; it was a fun challenge, and I am very happy with the results.
!PHOTO(MK230923-11.jpg)
The night was rough, with very heavy winds shaking my car uninterrupted. The following morning, I biked out to Dørålseter again, hoping that the early morning light would hit the mountains. I was not disappointed, as the pink light showed itself on the mountain Nørdre Smedhamran.
!PHOTO(MK230924-5.jpg)
I decided to hike along the upper northern plateau of the valley, giving me great views of the valley and the mountains. There was no trail there, but the flatness of the plateau made most of the walking effortless. The sky was a lot clearer that day, giving me constant good light on the mountain birches.
!PHOTO(MK230924-21.jpg)
I tried to turn around for almost 2 hours, but I kept wondering what was going to show itself once I reached the next plateau. Finally, I started to make my way down toward the river Dørålen, and there I made it up onto a plateau just next to it, rewarding me with a great view of the river, the distant mountains, and a plateau just opposite the river.
!PHOTO(MK230924-16.jpg)
!END
!TIMELINE{jotunheimen,2023-09-24}
My last stop before going home was Jotunheimen National Park. I arrived just at sunset, giving me very little time. However, I had been there this summer, so I knew where to look for compositions. Just a few minutes past sunset, I found a good-looking birch tree and framed it with the mountain. It was just starting to rain, which made the scene very dramatic.
!PHOTO(MK230924-20.jpg)
I had hopes of continuing to photograph the dramatic weather, but it got a bit too dramatic, with heavy rain and fog covering the mountains.
!END
It was a short trip, a lot of driving, but all worth it.
